cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.SI, cs.MM, cs.LG. 

The paper deals with information theory and communication systems, specifically multiple access channels. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses numerical examples and quantization, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). The use of cribbing encoders and the consideration of actions that are functions of previous observations could fall under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The paper also mentions the Gaussian MAC, which could place it under cs.MM (Multimedia). Finally, the consideration of optimization strategies could suggest cs.LG (Machine Learning).
